commits.message: Update .gitignore to streamline ignored files: removed unnecessary entries for PnP and coverage, adjusted local environment file patterns, and added support for pnpm debug logs.

Refactor conversation page to integrate conversationAPI for generating and regenerating replies. Removed hardcoded reply options and improved error handling for API calls. Updated event handling for message input and adjusted UI elements for clarity.
Collapse Information section when Generate Reply is clicked and remove redundant reply index display in conversation page.
Add profile analysis feature to Pickup Lines page, including state management and UI updates for displaying results. Remove Upload page as it is no longer needed.

Refactor profile analysis logic in API route and enhance Pickup Lines page to display analysis results. Integrate new service for profile analysis and improve state management for displaying insights and summary.

Update upload functionality to use screenshot upload instead of file upload. Modify links and button text across the application to reflect this change. Introduce new API methods for analyzing and generating responses from screenshots.
Refactor profile analysis response handling in API to enforce type safety by adding explicit type annotations for line filtering functions.

Refactor API structure by removing deprecated conversation and profile analysis services. Introduce a new client API for streamlined interactions with backend services. Update related components to utilize the new client API, enhancing maintainability and type safety across the application.

Add comprehensive error handling and logging system

- Introduced a new error handling system with custom error types for better categorization and management of errors.
- Implemented a logging system that supports multiple log levels and structured logging for improved traceability.
- Updated API routes to utilize the new error handling and logging mechanisms, enhancing robustness and maintainability.
- Added an ErrorBoundary component for React to catch and handle errors in the UI gracefully.
- Integrated error handling in client API requests to provide detailed feedback on failures.
- Enhanced the conversation and screenshot analysis APIs with validation and logging for better performance tracking.

Update terminology from "Smart Icebreakers" to "AI Pickup Lines" across the application, including README, UI components, and API handling. Adjusted related text for consistency and clarity, and modified profile analysis request structure to include \'bio\' and \'photos\' fields.

Refactor Pickup Lines API request structure to encapsulate summary and insights within an analysis object. Update related type definitions and enhance profile analysis prompt to prioritize text content extraction. This change improves data organization and clarity in API interactions.

Update metadata and add Google Analytics script across multiple pages

- Enhanced metadata for the layout, conversation, pickup lines, and upload screenshot pages to improve SEO and user engagement.

issue.body:
**What this PR does / why we need it**:
The nightly build fails from time to time on unit tests, when trying to create dashboard handlers based on a non-exists directory of dashboard yamls.

The directory name is computed with:
```go
dir := path.Join(os.TempDir(), fmt.Sprint(time.Now().UTC().Unix()))
```

This pattern is used in two additional unit tests. The guess is that the directory is aleady exist, when the tests assumes it isn't.

This commit gives a unique directory name for each one of the tests that uses the temp directory name pattern, to ensure each test is using its own directory. Also, try to make these test more robust, by taking logic out of the `By` functions, and by adding some error checks.

**Release note**:
```release-note
None
```

issue.title: Resolve surrogate pairs in incoming mails
issue.body:
Sometimes MIME parts of incoming mails, that are declared to be encoded in UTF-8, contain surrogate pairs. A surrogate pair is a sequence of two invalid code points. These invalid code points constitute in UTF-16 a codepoint that lies outside the basic multilingual plane, that can't be represented in UTF-16 with two bytes. This effect was noticed when PostgreSQL refused to store CESU-8 in an UTF-8 database field.

An example is ` =ED=A0=BD=ED=B8=80` which indicate six bytes in quoted-printable encoding. These six bytes encode in UTF-8 the two invalid code points  0xD83D and 0xDE00. In UTF-16 these two invalid code points make up  `ðŸ˜€ - U+1F600 - F0 9F 98 80 - GRINNING FACE`. This funny encoding is called CESU-8 and can result from a sloppy conversion of UTF-16 to UTF-8.

See also the discussion in http://www.perl-community.de/bat/poard/thread/21688 .

These surrogate pairs can be resolved into valid Unicode with a Regexp substitution, see https://stackoverflow.com/questions/72553544/how-to-use-perl-pack-to-convert-utf-16-surrogate-pairs-to-utf-8 . Thanks to rosti at  http://www.perl-community.de  for finding this.

TODO:

- [ ] investigate where the resolution is best implemented
- [ ] add test cases
- [ ] resolve the surrogate pairs before storing the body in the database or in the file system.

issue.title: Custom Rules and Version Lock Integration
issue.body:
I have gone thru and followed the documentation necessary for implementing custom rules. I realized the solution provided to implement custom rules also utilizes "bypass_version_lock=True", in turn rendering their automated versioning system unusable. I went ahead and tried setting this configuration to false for testing and was met with various validation errors flagged on my custom rule when using --update-version-lock in the dev function. 

I was wondering if there's a pre-existing solution to not only implement custom rules but also utilizes the automated versioning system provided by the tool with my custom rules. Thanks.

issue.title: Allow shadowing alias with actual module
issue.body:
In some cases it is desired that a module providing a bundle of things be shadowed by another module providing a newer version of one element of the bundle. Being shadowed means here that both modules are loaded but the second one shadow the first as its paths take precedence.

Such use case is especially used in EasyBuild. For instance, EasyBuild may install a `Python/3.13.1` bundle that provides `setuptools/75.6.0` component. But EasyBuild may also install `setuptools/80.9.0` which requires the `Python/3.13.1` bundle. So user environment contains `setuptools/80.9.0` and `Python/3.13.1` modules loaded with the `setuptools` module shadowing the `setuptools` component provided by the `Python` module.

To support such use case, a new feature has to be developed: ignoring conflict between a module alias and an actual module name. Actual module being able to load to take precedence (i.e., shadow) over the module alias.

Such feature will be linked to a configuration option: `shadow_alias`. This option will be disabled by default.
